03498nam a22004575i 9780773586673DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20112011xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735866737 a10.1515/97807735866732doi  a(DE-B1597)655341  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPHI0090002bisacsh04a301.09441 aFalasca-Zamponi, Simonetta, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRethinking the Political :bThe Sacred, Aesthetic Politics, and the Collège de Sociologie /cSimonetta Falasca-Zamponi. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v5500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tRepresenting the Social: Émile Durkheim and Marcel Mauss -- tAgainst Aesthetics: The Anthropology of Objects -- tThe Avant-Garde Meets Politics -- tFrom Contre-Attaque to the Collège: A Headless Interlude -- tAt the Collège: The Social in Excess -- tPolitics at the Collège -- tRethinking the Political -- tConclusions -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRethinking the Political demonstrates that the Collège de Sociologie's quest to create a new place for the sacred in modern collective life ostensibly entailed avoiding the theorization of both aesthetics and politics. While the Collège condemned manipulation by totalitarian regimes, its understanding of community also led to a rejection of democratic and communist forms of political organization, leaving the group open to accusations of flirting with fascism. Acknowledging these political ambiguities, the author goes beyond a narrow ideological reading to reveal the Collège's important contribution to our thinking about the relationships between community formation, politics, aesthetics, and the sacred in the modern world. She expands her historical account of the members' thought, including their relationship to Surrealism, beyond the group's dissolution, and shows how the work of Claude Lefort extends, but also resolves, many of the Collège's key theoretical insights. A fascinating study of some of the twentieth-century's most daring thinkers, Rethinking the Political offers crucial insights into the contradictions at play in modern notions of community that still resonate today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSociologyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358667340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773586673423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773586673/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles